     <exercises>
      <title>Converting Between Radical Notations and Rational Exponent Notation</title>

      <exercise>
        <title>Explanation and examples</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The power to a power rule of exponents states that <m>(x^m)^n=x^{mn}</m>.  This rule is fairly intuitive when both exponents are positive.  For example, in the expression <m>(x^4)^3</m> there are three factors of <m>x^4</m>, each of which contains four factors of <m>x</m>, so all together there are four factors of <m>x</m>, three times, i.e. <m>3 \cdot 4</m> factor of <m>x</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          While the power to a power rule is less intuitive once you move away from positive integer exponents, the rule remains the same regardless of the nature of the exponents.  For example:
          <md>
            <mrow>(x^{1/3})^3\amp=x^{\frac{1}{3} \cdot 3}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=x^{1}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=x</mrow>
          </md>
          But we already have a name for the expression that when cubed results in <m>x</m>, and that name is <m>\sqrt[3]{x}</m> (the cube root of <m>x</m>).  So it must be the case that <m>x^{1/3}=\sqrt[3]{x}</m>.  In general, is <m>n</m> is any positive integer, then: <me>x^{1/n}=\sqrt[n]{x}</me> and more generally, <me>x^{m/n}=\sqrt[n]{x^m}</me>.
        </p>
        Several examples are shown below.
        <sidebyside widths="33% 33% 33%" margins="0%">
          <p>
            <me>y^{7/5}=\sqrt[5]{y^7}</me>
          </p>
          <p>
            <md>
              <mrow>\sqrt[3]{w^{12}}\amp=w^{12/3}</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp=w^4</mrow>
            </md>
          </p>
          <p>
            <me>\sqrt{x^9}=x^{9/2}</me>
          </p>
        </sidebyside>
      </statement>
      </exercise>

      <exercise>
        <title>Practice exercises with detailed solutions</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Convert each exponential expression to a radical expression and each radical expression to an exponential expression.  When converting to a rational exponent, reduce the exponent if possible.  Assume that all variables represent positive values.
          <ol cols="3">
            <li><m>x^{1/3}</m></li>
            <li><m>y^{5/4}</m></li>
            <li><m>z^{2/5}</m></li>
            <li><m>\sqrt[11]{x^5}</m></li>
            <li><m>\sqrt[4]{y^{20}}</m></li>
            <li><m>\sqrt[15]{t^3}</m></li>
          </ol>
          <p>
          </p>
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p>
          <ol cols="2">
            <li><m>x^{1/3}=\sqrt[3]{x}</m></li>
            <li><m>y^{5/4}=\sqrt[4]{y^5}</m></li>
            <li><m>z^{2/5}=\sqrt[5]{z^2}</m></li>
            <li><m>\sqrt[11]{x^5}=x^{5/11}</m></li>

            <li>
              <m>
                \begin{aligned}[t]
                \sqrt[4]{y^{20}}\amp=y^{20/4}\\
                \amp=y^5
                \end{aligned}
              </m>            
            </li>

            <li>
              <m>
                \begin{aligned}[t]
                \sqrt[15]{t^3}\amp=t^{3/15}\\
                \amp=t^{1/5}
                \end{aligned}
